</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></code></pre></div></div>

<p>Uh-oh‚Ä¶ that ‚Äúmust be replaced‚Äù meant that terraform removed ALL the rules from this resource and then took a few seconds to put them back. That doesn‚Äôt sound too bad, but if you‚Äôre a large site getting several (or several thousand) hits per second, you just had 2s of downtime even for the CIDRs you didn‚Äôt touch. There go your ‚Äúnines‚Äù.</p>

<p>Unless we‚Äôre feeling super-cool and want to go re-write the terraform aws provider to try to be more clever about that, this isn‚Äôt going to work. The previous approach also had the same issue, as we alluded earlier.</p>

<h4> Method the Third - count the aws_security_group_rules </h4>
<p>Ok, so we <em>could</em> split up that resource into multiple terraform resources, that should let us replace or remove one without impacting the others, right?</p>
<div class="language-terraform highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><table class="rouge-table"><tbody><tr><td class="rouge-gutter gl"><pre class="lineno">1
